%S A397067 2,5,11,17,41,59,67,127,157,211,277,307,331,347,367,389,401,607,653,
%T A397067 907,967,977,1153,1297,1567,1669,1697,1801,1873,2027,2221,2417,2659,
%U A397067 2731,2749,2927,2963,3037,3517,3581,3593,3929,4007,4159,4217,4229,4339,4441
%N A397067 Primes prime(k) such that the sum of the k primes beginning with prime(k) is prime.
%H A397067 James C. McMahon, <a href="/A397067/b397067.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..1000</a>
%F A397067 a(n) = A000040(A397068(n)).
%e A397067 11 is the fifth prime. The sum of the five primes beginning with 11 is 11 + 13 + 17 + 19 + 23 = 83, which is prime.
%e A397067 3 is the second prime. The sum of the two primes beginning with 3 is 3 + 5 = 8, which is not prime; therefore, 3 is not a term.
%t A397067 q[k_]:=PrimeQ[Sum[Prime[i],{i,k,k+k-1}]];Prime/@Select[Range[700],q]
%o A397067 (Python)
%o A397067 from sympy import prime, isprime
%o A397067 def q(k):
%o A397067     return isprime(sum(prime(i) for i in range(k, 2 * k)))
%o A397067 print([prime(k) for k in range(1, 501) if q(k)])
%Y A397067 Cf. A000040, A013917, A161463, A397068, A397069.
%K A397067 nonn
